00:50:00.910 --> 00:50:07.170
If I miss some, call me out,
and I'll try to come back to it.

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:08.790
So there's a lot in there.

00:50:08.790 --> 00:50:12.600
Part of is it's very
hard to go against what

00:50:12.600 --> 00:50:15.600
you've been taught and
trained and society around to

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:18.570
tells you feels right.

00:50:18.570 --> 00:50:21.509
There's all this stuff out
there about follow your heart.

00:50:21.509 --> 00:50:22.800
It's easy to follow your heart.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:24.450
It's a lot harder
to follow your brain

00:50:24.450 --> 00:50:26.880
when your heart, and your
feelings, and people around you

00:50:26.880 --> 00:50:29.160
are telling you
something different.

00:50:29.160 --> 00:50:33.810
I think it helps a lot to remind
yourself that the worst case

00:50:33.810 --> 00:50:37.840
scenario is not that bad because
it is a reversible decision.

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:39.960
I don't think anyone
should make a unilateral,

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:42.630
I will never send
my kids to college.

00:50:42.630 --> 00:50:44.130
I do think everyone
should move away

00:50:44.130 --> 00:50:48.289
from the default, that option A
is that my kids go to college.

00:50:48.289 --> 00:50:50.580
Let them chart their path,
figure out what makes sense.

00:50:50.580 --> 00:50:54.690
And if it turns out
to be college, OK.

00:50:54.690 --> 00:50:56.440
There are a lot of
other paths to success.

00:50:56.440 --> 00:51:02.130
I also think there's an unfair
and unreasonable bar for going

00:51:02.130 --> 00:51:04.200
to college versus not.

00:51:04.200 --> 00:51:09.450
If you go to college, success
means you land a good job.

00:51:09.450 --> 00:51:12.375
You make a high five-figure,
low six-figure income.

00:51:12.375 --> 00:51:15.180
That's, like, you know,
the bar for success.

00:51:15.180 --> 00:51:17.610
You say, well, I think I'm
not going to go to college.

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:19.692
And other people have
been successful not

00:51:19.692 --> 00:51:20.400
going to college.

00:51:20.400 --> 00:51:21.270
Yeah, but you're not Bill Gates.

00:51:21.270 --> 00:51:22.680
You're not Mark Zuckerberg.

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:26.490
So if the bar for success
for going to college

00:51:26.490 --> 00:51:29.040
is a six-figure
income, why is the bar

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:33.050
for success for not going to
college becoming a billionaire?

00:51:33.050 --> 00:51:35.230
Like, that doesn't make sense.

00:51:35.230 --> 00:51:36.710
That's not how ROI works.

00:51:36.710 --> 00:51:39.900
So I would just keep
all of that in mind.

00:51:39.900 --> 00:51:43.512
And the counterargument is--

00:51:43.512 --> 00:51:44.970
one of the things
I didn't touch on

00:51:44.970 --> 00:51:47.420
is that a big reason
why the value of college

00:51:47.420 --> 00:51:52.470
is declined aside from the
internal actual value of what

00:51:52.470 --> 00:51:54.570
it prepares you to do
and all that, college

00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.146
has been a signal.

00:51:56.146 --> 00:51:58.020
It's been a signal that,
look, the person who

00:51:58.020 --> 00:52:00.020
bears this has gone through
certain experiences,

00:52:00.020 --> 00:52:03.300
has certain wherewithal
and financial resources,

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:06.180
comes from a certain echelon of
society, et cetera, et cetera.

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:08.901
And the value of that
signal is declining

00:52:08.901 --> 00:52:10.650
for all the reasons
we discussed, but also

00:52:10.650 --> 00:52:12.430
because of ubiquity, right?

00:52:12.430 --> 00:52:14.790
It used to be that you
apply for a job 40 years ago

00:52:14.790 --> 00:52:18.910
and your rsum has MBA after
your name, you're the only one.

00:52:18.910 --> 00:52:19.680
So you stand out.

00:52:19.680 --> 00:52:21.640
If everyone has an
undergraduate degree,

00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:23.410
you don't stand out at all.

00:52:23.410 --> 00:52:25.176
And if you don't,
it might actually

00:52:25.176 --> 00:52:26.550
be an interesting
differentiator.

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:29.277
Well, what has this
person does instead?

00:52:29.277 --> 00:52:31.110
And so that's the reason
why it's gone down.

00:52:31.110 --> 00:52:35.460
That said, that ubiquity
is kind of shift--

00:52:35.460 --> 00:52:37.560
and that's part of why
the decline in the value--

00:52:37.560 --> 00:52:39.930
it's kind of shifted
what the degree signals.

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:42.330
It used to say, look,
the bearer of this degree

00:52:42.330 --> 00:52:44.610
is better than everyone else.

00:52:44.610 --> 00:52:46.830
Now, it says, the
bearer of this degree

00:52:46.830 --> 00:52:49.320
is no worse than anyone else.

00:52:49.320 --> 00:52:54.660
And, unfortunately-- and I hate
to say this-- but for people

00:52:54.660 --> 00:52:56.940
in society who are in a
position where they will not

00:52:56.940 --> 00:52:59.377
be given the benefit
of the doubt,

00:52:59.377 --> 00:53:00.960
where whether it's
women, whether it's

00:53:00.960 --> 00:53:03.000
people of color,
people who are coming

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.312
from a disadvantaged
position, that stamp of, look,

00:53:06.312 --> 00:53:07.770
you're no better
than everyone else

00:53:07.770 --> 00:53:09.311
but you're no worse
than anyone else,

00:53:09.311 --> 00:53:11.950
either, could have more value.

00:53:11.950 --> 00:53:14.260
So I don't advocate
it in general.

00:53:14.260 --> 00:53:16.220
And I think there
are good reasons to.

00:53:16.220 --> 00:53:17.720
If you're going to
do it, find a way

00:53:17.720 --> 00:53:19.460
to do it that is cost effective.

00:53:19.460 --> 00:53:24.392
But that could skew the math.

